[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning is generally concerned with and motivated by issues such as data privacy, data minimization, and data access rights.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Its applications involve a variety of research areas including defence, telecommunications, the Internet of things, and pharmaceuticals.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning aims at training a machine learning algorithm, for instance deep neural networks, on multiple local datasets contained in local nodes without explicitly exchanging data samples.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The general principle consists in training local models on local data samples and exchanging parameters (e.g. the weights and biases of a deep neural network) between these local nodes at some frequency to generate a global model shared by all nodes.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The main difference between federated learning and distributed learning lies in the assumptions made on the properties of the local datasets, as distributed learning originally aims at parallelizing computing power where federated learning originally aims at training on heterogeneous datasets.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] While distributed learning also aims at training a single model on multiple servers, a common underlying assumption is that the local datasets are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) and roughly have the same size.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] None of these hypotheses are made for federated learning; instead, the datasets are typically heterogeneous and their sizes may span several orders of magnitude.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Moreover, the clients involved in federated learning may be unreliable as they are subject to more failures or drop out since they commonly rely on less powerful communication media (i.e.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Wi-Fi) and battery-powered systems (i.e. smartphones and IoT devices) compared to distributed learning where nodes are typically datacenters that have powerful computational capabilities and are connected to one another with fast networks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] where K is the number of nodes, $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ are the weights of model as viewed by node i , and $f_{i}$ is node i 's local objective function, which describes how model weights $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ conforms to node i 's local dataset.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In the centralized federated learning setting, a central server is used to orchestrate the different steps of the algorithms and coordinate all the participating nodes during the learning process.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The server is responsible for the nodes selection at the beginning of the training process and for the aggregation of the received model updates.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Since all the selected nodes have to send updates to a single entity, the server may become a bottleneck of the system.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In the decentralized federated learning setting, the nodes are able to coordinate themselves to obtain the global model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This setup prevents single point failures as the model updates are exchanged only between interconnected nodes without the orchestration of the central server.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Nevertheless, the specific network topology may affect the performances of the learning process.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] See blockchain-based federated learning and the references therein.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In many application domains, not all clients are the same.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Clients may share the same model architecture, but each have a different data distribution—which is known as Personalized federated learning (PFL), or even have different model architectures, like mobile phones and IoT devices—which is known as Heterogeneous federated learning.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The key challenge in training a PFL model is to keep each client different from others, and at the same time benefit from generalizing across clients.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Most of the existing federated learning strategies assume that local models share the same global model architecture.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In 2020, a federated learning framework named HeteroFL was developed to address heterogeneous clients equipped with very different computation and communication capabilities.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The HeteroFL technique can enable the training of heterogeneous local models with dynamically varying computation and non-IID data complexities while still producing a single accurate global inference model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The iterative process of federated learning is composed of a series of fundamental client-server interactions, each of which is known as a federated learning round.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In the methodology below, a central server is used for aggregation, while local nodes perform local training depending on the central server's orders.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] However, other strategies lead to the same results without central servers, in a peer-to-peer approach, using gossip or consensus methodologies.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] **Client selection**: a fraction of local nodes are selected to start training on local data.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The selected nodes acquire the current statistical model while the others wait for the next federated round.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] **Configuration**: the central server orders selected nodes to undergo training of the model on their local data in a pre-specified fashion (e.g., for some mini-batch updates of gradient descent).
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] **Reporting**: each selected node sends its local model to the server for aggregation.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The central server aggregates the received models and sends back the model updates to the nodes.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] It also handles failures for disconnected nodes or lost model updates.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The next federated round is started returning to the client selection phase.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] **Termination**: once a pre-defined termination criterion is met (e.g., a maximum number of iterations is reached or the model accuracy is greater than a threshold) the central server aggregates the updates and finalizes the global model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The procedure considered before assumes synchronized model updates.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Recent federated learning developments introduced novel techniques to tackle asynchronicity during the training process, or training with dynamically varying models.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Compared to synchronous approaches where local models are exchanged once the computations have been performed for all layers of the neural network, asynchronous ones leverage the properties of neural networks to exchange model updates as soon as the computations of a certain layer are available.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] These techniques are also commonly referred to as split learning and they can be applied both at training and inference time regardless of centralized or decentralized federated learning settings.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In most cases, the assumption of independent and identically distributed samples across local nodes does not hold for federated learning setups.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Under this setting, the performances of the training process may vary significantly according to the unbalanced local data samples as well as the particular probability distribution of the training examples (i.e., features and labels) stored at the local nodes.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] To further investigate the effects of non-IID data, the following description considers the main categories presented in the preprint by Peter Kairouz et al. from 2019.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The description of non-IID data relies on the analysis of the joint probability between features and labels for each node.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This allows decoupling of each contribution according to the specific distribution available at the local nodes.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The loss in accuracy due to non-iid data can be bounded through using more sophisticated means of doing data normalization, rather than batch normalization.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The way the statistical local outputs are pooled and the way the nodes communicate with each other can change from the centralized model explained in the previous section.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This leads to a variety of federated learning approaches: for instance no central orchestrating server, or stochastic communication.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In particular, orchestrator-less distributed networks are one important variation.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In this case, there is no central server dispatching queries to local nodes and aggregating local models.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Each local node sends its outputs to several randomly-selected others, which aggregate their results locally.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This restrains the number of transactions, thereby sometimes reducing training time and computing cost.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Those parameters have to be optimized depending on the constraints of the machine learning application (e.g., available computing power, available memory, bandwidth).
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] For instance, stochastically choosing a limited fraction C of nodes for each iteration diminishes computing cost and may prevent overfitting, in the same way that stochastic gradient descent can reduce overfitting.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning requires frequent communication between nodes during the learning process.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Thus, it requires not only enough local computing power and memory, but also high bandwidth connections to be able to exchange parameters of the machine learning model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] However, the technology also avoids data communication, which can require significant resources before starting centralized machine learning.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Governance considerations may also limit the applicability of federated learning, in particular when applied in cross-organisational settings.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Most federated learning frameworks rely on a central coordinating server, which introduces questions regarding infrastructure control, model ownership, and decision-making authority among collaborators.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In multi-party deployments, especially those spanning competitive or collaborative data markets, the absence of agreed-upon governance structures can create uncertainty about responsibilities for validating model updates, auditing system behaviour, and managing security incidents.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] These organisational issues may deter participants from contributing to shared models and can complicate regulatory compliance, thereby constraining adoption.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] A further governance-related issue concerns the distribution of value among participants as multi-party federated learning systems scale.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] As more clients contribute to training, model accuracy may approach a performance threshold, after which additional contributions yield diminishing marginal utility.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This dynamic can create tensions within collaborative arrangements, as early participants may perceive later contributions as offering reduced value while still benefiting from the shared model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Such asymmetries may affect incentives to join or remain in a consortium and complicate the design of fair participation, ownership, or reward structures.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Establishing transparent rules for contribution assessment and benefit allocation is therefore an important organisational challenge and represents a direction for future research.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] A number of different algorithms for federated optimization have been proposed.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Stochastic gradient descent is an approach used in deep learning, where gradients are computed on a random subset of the total dataset and then used to make one step of the gradient descent..
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated stochastic gradient descent is the analog of this algorithm to the federated setting, but uses a random subset of the nodes, each node using all its data.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The server averages the gradients in proportion to the number of training data on each node, and uses the average to make a gradient descent step.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated averaging (FedAvg) is a generalization of FedSGD which allows nodes to do more than one batch update on local data and exchange updated weights rather than gradients.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This reduces communication and is equivalent to averaging the weights if all nodes start with the same weights.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] It does not seem to hurt the resulting averaged model's performance compared to FedSGD.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] FedAvg variations have been proposed based on adaptive optimizers such as ADAM and AdaGrad, and tend to outperform FedAvg.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated Proximal (FedProx) extends FedAvg by adding a proximal term to the local objective in the form of ${\frac {\mu }{2}}\|w-w^{t}\|^{2}$ , where $\mu$ is the FedProx hyper parameter, in order to address data heterogeneity across clients.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The proximal term constrains local updates, helping reduce client drift when client data are non-IID.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning methods suffer when node datasets are distributed heterogeneously, because then minimizing the node losses is not the same as minimizing the global loss.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In 2021, Acar et al. introduced a solution called FedDyn, which dynamically regularizes each node loss function so that they converge to the global loss.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Since the local losses are aligned, FedDyn is robust to the different heterogeneity levels and so it can safely perform full minimization in each device.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In theory, FedDyn converges to the optimal (a stationary point for nonconvex losses) by being agnostic to the heterogeneity levels.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] These claims are verified with extensive experiments on various datasets.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Besides reducing communication, it is also beneficial to reduce local computation.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] To do this, FedDynOneGD modifies FedDyn to calculate only one gradient per node per round, regularizes it and updates the global model with it.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Hence, the computational complexity is linear in local dataset size.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Moreover, gradient computation can be parallelized on each node, unlike successive SGD steps.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In theory, FedDynOneGD achieves the same convergence guarantees as in FedDyn with less local computation.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning methods have poor global performance under non-IID settings.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This motivates clients to yield personalized models in federation.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] To change this, Vahidian et al. recently introduced the algorithm Sub-FedAvg which does hybrid pruning (structured and unstructured pruning) with averaging on the intersection of clients' drawn subnetworks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This simultaneously addresses communication efficiency, resource constraints and personalized models accuracies.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Sub-FedAvg also extends the "lottery ticket hypothesis" of centrally trained neural networks to federated learning, with the research question: "Do winning tickets exist for clients' neural networks being trained in federated learning?
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] If so, how to effectively draw the personalized subnetworks for each client?" Sub-FedAvg experimentally answers "yes" and proposes two algorithms to effectively draw the personalized subnetworks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] IDA (Inverse Distance Aggregation) is a novel adaptive weighting approach for federated learning nodes based on meta-information which handles unbalanced and non-iid data.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] It uses the distance of the model parameters as a strategy to minimize the effect of outliers and improve the model's convergence rate.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Very few methods for hybrid federated learning, where clients only hold subsets of both features and samples, exist.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Yet, this scenario is very important in practical settings.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Hybrid Federated Dual Coordinate Ascent (HyFDCA) is a novel algorithm proposed in 2024 that solves convex problems in the hybrid FL setting.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This algorithm extends CoCoA, a primal-dual distributed optimization algorithm introduced by Jaggi et al.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] (2017), to the case where both samples and features are partitioned across clients.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] There is only one other algorithm that focuses on hybrid FL, HyFEM proposed by Zhang et al.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This algorithm uses a feature matching formulation that balances clients building accurate local models and the server learning an accurate global model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This requires a matching regularizer constant that must be tuned based on user goals and results in disparate local and global models.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Furthermore, the convergence results provided for HyFEM only prove convergence of the matching formulation not of the original global problem.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] This work is substantially different from HyFDCA's approach which uses data on local clients to build a global model that converges to the same solution as if the model was trained centrally.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Furthermore, the local and global models are synchronized and do not require the adjustment of a matching parameter between local and global models.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] However, HyFEM is suitable for a vast array of architectures including deep learning architectures, whereas HyFDCA is designed for convex problems like logistic regression and support vector machines.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] HyFDCA is empirically benchmarked against the aforementioned HyFEM as well as the popular FedAvg in solving convex problem (specifically classification problems) for several popular datasets (MNIST, Covtype, and News20).
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The authors found HyFDCA converges to a lower loss value and higher validation accuracy in less overall time in 33 of 36 comparisons examined and 36 of 36 comparisons examined with respect to the number of outer iterations.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Lastly, HyFDCA only requires tuning of one hyperparameter, the number of inner iterations, as opposed to FedAvg (which requires tuning three) or HyFEM (which requires tuning four).
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In addition to FedAvg and HyFEM being quite difficult to optimize hyperparameters in turn greatly affecting convergence, HyFDCA's single hyperparameter allows for simpler practical implementations and hyperparameter selection methodologies.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning has started to emerge as an important research topic in 2015 and 2016, with the first publications on federated averaging in telecommunication settings.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Before that, in a thesis work titled "A Framework for Multi-source Prefetching Through Adaptive Weight", an approach to aggregate predictions from multiple models trained at three location of a request response cycle with was proposed.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Another important aspect of active research is the reduction of the communication burden during the federated learning process.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In 2017 and 2018, publications have emphasized the development of resource allocation strategies, especially to reduce communication requirements between nodes with gossip algorithms as well as on the characterization of the robustness to differential privacy attacks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Other research activities focus on the reduction of the bandwidth during training through sparsification and quantization methods, where the machine learning models are sparsified and/or compressed before they are shared with other nodes.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Developing ultra-light DNN architectures is essential for device-/edge- learning and recent work recognises both the energy efficiency requirements for future federated learning and the need to compress deep learning, especially during learning.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Recent research advancements are starting to consider real-world propagating channels as in previous implementations ideal channels were assumed.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Another active direction of research is to develop Federated learning for training heterogeneous local models with varying computation complexities and producing a single powerful global inference model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] A learning framework named Assisted learning was recently developed to improve each agent's learning capabilities without transmitting private data, models, and even learning objectives.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Compared with Federated learning that often requires a central controller to orchestrate the learning and optimization, Assisted learning aims to provide protocols for the agents to optimize and learn among themselves without a global model.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning typically applies when individual actors need to train models on larger datasets than their own, but cannot afford to share the data in itself with others (e.g., for legal, strategic or economic reasons).
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The technology yet requires good connections between local servers and minimum computational power for each node.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Self-driving cars encapsulate many machine learning technologies to function: computer vision for analyzing obstacles, machine learning for adapting their pace to the environment (e.g., bumpiness of the road).
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Due to the potential high number of self-driving cars and the need for them to quickly respond to real world situations, traditional cloud approach may generate safety risks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning can represent a solution for limiting volume of data transfer and accelerating learning processes.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In Industry 4.0, there is a widespread adoption of machine learning techniques to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of industrial process while guaranteeing a high level of safety.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Nevertheless, privacy of sensitive data for industries and manufacturing companies is of paramount importance.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning algorithms can be applied to these problems as they do not disclose any sensitive data.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In addition, FL also implemented for PM2.5 prediction to support Smart city sensing applications.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated learning seeks to address the problem of data governance and privacy by training algorithms collaboratively without exchanging the data itself.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Today's standard approach of centralizing data from multiple centers comes at the cost of critical concerns regarding patient privacy and data protection.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] To solve this problem, the ability to train machine learning models at scale across multiple medical institutions without moving the data is a critical technology.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Recently, a collaboration of 20 different institutions around the world validated the utility of training AI models using federated learning.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In a paper published in Nature Medicine "Federated learning for predicting clinical outcomes in patients with COVID-19", they showcased the accuracy and generalizability of a federated AI model for the prediction of oxygen needs in patients with COVID-19 infections.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Furthermore, in a published paper "A Systematic Review of Federated Learning in the Healthcare Area: From the Perspective of Data Properties and Applications", the authors trying to provide a set of challenges on FL challenges on medical data-centric perspective.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] A coalition from industry and academia has developed MedPerf, an open source platform that enables validation of medical AI models in real world data.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] The platform relies technically on federated evaluation of AI models aiming to alleviate concerns of patient privacy and conceptually on diverse benchmark committees to build the specifications of neutral clinically impactful benchmarks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Robotics includes a wide range of applications of machine learning methods: from perception and decision-making to control.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] As robotic technologies have been increasingly deployed from simple and repetitive tasks (e.g. repetitive manipulation) to complex and unpredictable tasks (e.g. autonomous navigation), the need for machine learning grows.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated Learning provides a solution to improve over conventional machine learning training methods.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In the paper, mobile robots learned navigation over diverse environments using the FL-based method, helping generalization.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In the paper, Federated Learning is applied to improve multi-robot navigation under limited communication bandwidth scenarios, which is a current challenge in real-world learning-based robotic tasks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] In the paper, Federated Learning is used to learn Vision-based navigation, helping better sim-to-real transfer.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Federated Learning (FL) is transforming biometric recognition by enabling collaborative model training across distributed data sources while preserving privacy.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] By eliminating the need to share sensitive biometric templates like fingerprints, facial images, and iris scans, FL addresses privacy concerns and regulatory constraints, allowing for improved model accuracy and generalizability.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] It mitigates challenges of data fragmentation by leveraging scattered datasets, making it particularly effective for diverse biometric applications such as facial and iris recognition.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] However, FL faces challenges, including model and data heterogeneity, computational overhead, and vulnerability to security threats like inference attacks.
[src:secure-aggregation/federated-learning] Future directions include developing personalized FL frameworks, enhancing system efficiency, and expanding FL applications to biometric presentation attack detection (PAD) and quality assessment, fostering innovation and robust solutions in privacy-sensitive environments.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] As an example of a practical application of homomorphic encryption: encrypted photographs can be scanned for points of interest, without revealing the contents of a photo.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] However, observation of side-channels can see a photograph being sent to a point-of-interest lookup service, revealing the fact that photographs were taken.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Thus, homomorphic encryption eliminates the need for processing data in the clear, thereby preventing attacks that would enable an attacker to access that data while it is being processed, using privilege escalation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] For sensitive data, such as healthcare information, homomorphic encryption can be used to enable new services by removing privacy barriers inhibiting data sharing or increasing security to existing services.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] For example, predictive analytics in healthcare can be hard to apply via a third-party service provider due to medical data privacy concerns.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] But if the predictive-analytics service provider could operate on encrypted data instead, without having the decryption keys, these privacy concerns are diminished.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Moreover, even if the service provider's system is compromised, the data would remain secure.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption is a form of encryption with an additional evaluation capability for computing over encrypted data without access to the secret key.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The result of such a computation remains encrypted.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption can be viewed as an extension of public-key cryptography, because ciphertexts can be manipulated algebraically to produce an encrypted result corresponding to operations on the underlying plaintexts.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] *Homomorphic* refers to homomorphism in algebra: the encryption and decryption functions can be thought of as homomorphisms between plaintext and ciphertext spaces.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption includes multiple types of encryption schemes that can perform different classes of computations over encrypted data.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The computations are represented as either Boolean or arithmetic circuits.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] For the majority of homomorphic encryption schemes, the multiplicative depth of circuits is the main practical limitation in performing computations over encrypted data.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes are inherently malleable.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] In terms of malleability, homomorphic encryption schemes have weaker security properties than non-homomorphic schemes.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] A cryptosystem that supports *arbitrary computation* on ciphertexts is known as fully homomorphic encryption (FHE).
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Such a scheme enables the construction of programs for any desirable functionality, which can be run on encrypted inputs to produce an encryption of the result.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Since such a program need never decrypt its inputs, it can be run by an untrusted party without revealing its inputs and internal state.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Fully homomorphic cryptosystems have great practical implications in the outsourcing of private computations, for instance, in the context of cloud computing.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Homomorphic encryption schemes have been developed using different approaches.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Specifically, fully homomorphic encryption schemes are often grouped into generations corresponding to the underlying approach.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The problem of constructing a fully homomorphic encryption scheme was first proposed in 1978, within a year of publishing of the RSA scheme.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] For more than 30 years, it was unclear whether a solution existed.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Craig Gentry, using lattice-based cryptography, described the first plausible construction for a fully homomorphic encryption scheme in 2009.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's scheme supports both addition and multiplication operations on ciphertexts, from which it is possible to construct circuits for performing arbitrary computation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry then shows how to slightly modify this scheme to make it *bootstrappable*, i.e., capable of evaluating its own decryption circuit and then at least one more operation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Finally, he shows that any bootstrappable somewhat homomorphic encryption scheme can be converted into a fully homomorphic encryption through a recursive self-embedding.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] For Gentry's "noisy" scheme, the bootstrapping procedure effectively "refreshes" the ciphertext by applying to it the decryption procedure homomorphically, thereby obtaining a new ciphertext that encrypts the same value as before but has lower noise.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] By "refreshing" the ciphertext periodically whenever the noise grows too large, it is possible to compute an arbitrary number of additions and multiplications without increasing the noise too much.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry based the security of his scheme on the assumed hardness of two problems: certain worst-case problems over ideal lattices, and the sparse (or low-weight) subset sum problem.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Gentry's Ph.D. thesis provides additional details.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The Gentry-Halevi implementation of Gentry's original cryptosystem reported a timing of about 30 minutes per basic bit operation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Extensive design and implementation work in subsequent years have improved upon these early implementations by many orders of magnitude runtime performance.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] In 2010, Marten van Dijk, Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi and Vinod Vaikuntanathan presented a second fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which uses many of the tools of Gentry's construction, but which does not require ideal lattices.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Instead, they show that the somewhat homomorphic component of Gentry's ideal lattice-based scheme can be replaced with a very simple somewhat homomorphic scheme that uses integers.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The scheme is therefore conceptually simpler than Gentry's ideal lattice scheme, but has similar properties with regards to homomorphic operations and efficiency.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The somewhat homomorphic component in the work of Van Dijk et al. is similar to an encryption scheme proposed by Levieil and Naccache in 2008, and also to one that was proposed by Bram Cohen in 1998.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Cohen's method is not even additively homomorphic, however.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The Levieil–Naccache scheme supports only additions, but it can be modified to also support a small number of multiplications.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Many refinements and optimizations of the scheme of Van Dijk et al. were proposed in a sequence of works by Jean-Sébastien Coron, Tancrède Lepoint, Avradip Mandal, David Naccache, and Mehdi Tibouchi.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Some of these works included also implementations of the resulting schemes.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The homomorphic cryptosystems of this generation are derived from techniques that were developed starting in 2011–2012 by Zvika Brakerski, Craig Gentry, Vinod Vaikuntanathan, and others.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] These innovations led to the development of much more efficient somewhat and fully homomorphic cryptosystems.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The security of most of these schemes is based on the hardness of the (Ring) Learning With Errors (RLWE) problem, except for the LTV and BLLN schemes that rely on an *overstretched* variant of the NTRU computational problem.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] This NTRU variant was subsequently shown vulnerable to subfield lattice attacks, which is why these two schemes are no longer used in practice.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] All the second-generation cryptosystems still follow the basic blueprint of Gentry's original construction, namely they first construct a somewhat homomorphic cryptosystem and then convert it to a fully homomorphic cryptosystem using bootstrapping.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] A distinguishing characteristic of the second-generation cryptosystems is that they all feature a much slower growth of the noise during the homomorphic computations.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Additional optimizations by Craig Gentry, Shai Halevi, and Nigel Smart resulted in cryptosystems with nearly optimal asymptotic complexity: Performing T operations on data encrypted with security parameter k has complexity of only $T\cdot \mathrm {polylog} (k)$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] These optimizations build on the Smart-Vercauteren techniques that enable packing of many plaintext values in a single ciphertext and operating on all these plaintext values in a SIMD fashion.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Many of the advances in these second-generation cryptosystems were also ported to the cryptosystem over the integers.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Another distinguishing feature of second-generation schemes is that they are efficient enough for many applications even without invoking bootstrapping, instead operating in the leveled FHE mode.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] In 2013, Craig Gentry, Amit Sahai, and Brent Waters (GSW) proposed a new technique for building FHE schemes that avoids an expensive "relinearization" step in homomorphic multiplication.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Zvika Brakerski and Vinod Vaikuntanathan observed that for certain types of circuits, the GSW cryptosystem features an even slower growth rate of noise, and hence better efficiency and stronger security.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Jacob Alperin-Sheriff and Chris Peikert then described a very efficient bootstrapping technique based on this observation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] These techniques were further improved to develop efficient ring variants of the GSW cryptosystem: FHEW (2014) and TFHE (2016).
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The FHEW scheme was the first to show that by refreshing the ciphertexts after every single operation, it is possible to reduce the bootstrapping time to a fraction of a second.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] FHEW introduced a new method to compute Boolean gates on encrypted data that greatly simplifies bootstrapping and implemented a variant of the bootstrapping procedure.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The efficiency of FHEW was further improved by the TFHE scheme, which implements a ring variant of the bootstrapping procedure using a method similar to the one in FHEW.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] In 2016, Jung Hee Cheon, Andrey Kim, Miran Kim, and Yongsoo Song (CKKS) proposed an approximate homomorphic encryption scheme that supports a special kind of fixed-point arithmetic that is commonly referred to as block floating point arithmetic.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The CKKS scheme includes an efficient rescaling operation that scales down an encrypted message after a multiplication.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] For comparison, such rescaling requires bootstrapping in the BGV and BFV schemes.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The rescaling operation makes CKKS scheme the most efficient method for evaluating polynomial approximations, and is the preferred approach for implementing privacy-preserving machine learning applications.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The scheme introduces several approximation errors, both nondeterministic and deterministic, that require special handling in practice.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] A 2020 article by Baiyu Li and Daniele Micciancio discusses passive attacks against CKKS, suggesting that the standard IND-CPA definition may not be sufficient in scenarios where decryption results are shared.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The authors apply the attack to four modern homomorphic encryption libraries (HEAAN, SEAL, HElib and PALISADE) and report that it is possible to recover the secret key from decryption results in several parameter configurations.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The authors also propose mitigation strategies for these attacks, and include a Responsible Disclosure in the paper suggesting that the homomorphic encryption libraries already implemented mitigations for the attacks before the article became publicly available.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Further information on the mitigation strategies implemented in the homomorphic encryption libraries has also been published.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] In the following examples, the notation ${\mathcal {E}}(x)$ is used to denote the encryption of the message x .
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] where $\oplus$ denotes addition modulo 2, (i.e., exclusive-or).
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] There are several open-source implementations of partially, somewhat and fully homomorphic encryption schemes.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Second-generation and fourth-generation FHE scheme implementations typically operate in the leveled FHE mode (though bootstrapping is still available in some libraries) and support efficient SIMD-like packing of data; they are typically used to compute on encrypted integers or real/complex numbers.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Third-generation FHE scheme implementations often bootstrap after each operation but have limited support for packing; they were initially used to compute Boolean circuits over encrypted bits, but have been extended to support integer arithmetics and univariate function evaluation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] The choice of using a second-generation vs. third-generation vs fourth-generation scheme depends on the input data types and the desired computation.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] General-purpose lattice cryptography library.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] TFHE-extended compiler with a Python Frontend.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] Verifiable encrypted computations based on Rinocchio ZKP and BGV homomorphic Encryption.
[src:secure-aggregation/homomorphic-encryption] In 2017, researchers from IBM, Microsoft, Intel, the NIST, and others formed the open Homomorphic Encryption Standardization Consortium, which maintains a community security Homomorphic Encryption Standard.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In cryptography, an **oblivious transfer** (**OT**) protocol is a type of protocol in which a sender transfers one of potentially many pieces of information to a receiver, but remains oblivious as to what piece (if any) has been transferred.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The first form of oblivious transfer was introduced in 1981 by Michael O.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In this form, the sender sends a message to the receiver with probability 1/2, while the sender remains oblivious as to whether or not the receiver received the message.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Rabin's oblivious transfer scheme is based on the RSA cryptosystem.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] A more useful form of oblivious transfer called **1–2 oblivious transfer** or "1 out of 2 oblivious transfer", was developed later by Shimon Even, Oded Goldreich, and Abraham Lempel, in order to build protocols for secure multiparty computation.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] It is generalized to "1 out of *n* oblivious transfer" where the user gets exactly one database element without the server getting to know which element was queried, and without the user knowing anything about the other elements that were not retrieved.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The latter notion of oblivious transfer is a strengthening of private information retrieval, in which the database is not kept private.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Claude Crépeau showed that Rabin's oblivious transfer is equivalent to 1–2 oblivious transfer.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Further work has revealed oblivious transfer to be a fundamental and important problem in cryptography.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] It is considered one of the critical problems in the field, because of the importance of the applications that can be built based on it.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In particular, it is complete for secure multiparty computation: that is, given an implementation of oblivious transfer it is possible to securely evaluate any polynomial time computable function without any additional primitive.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In Rabin's oblivious transfer protocol, the sender generates an RSA public modulus *N*=*pq* where *p* and *q* are large prime numbers, and an exponent *e* relatively prime to *λ(N)* = (*p* − 1)(*q* − 1).
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The sender encrypts the message *m* as *m**e* mod *N*.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The receiver picks a random *x* modulo *N* and sends *x*2 mod *N* to the sender.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Note that gcd(*x*,*N*) = 1 with overwhelming probability, which ensures that there are 4 square roots of *x*2 mod *N*.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The sender finds a square root *y* of *x*2 mod *N* and sends *y* to the receiver.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] If the receiver finds *y* is neither *x* nor −*x* modulo *N*, the receiver will be able to factor *N* and therefore decrypt *m**e* to recover *m* (see Rabin encryption for more details).
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] However, if *y* is *x* or −*x* mod *N*, the receiver will have no information about *m* beyond the encryption of it.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Since every quadratic residue modulo *N* has four square roots, the probability that the receiver learns *m* is 1/2.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In a 1–2 oblivious transfer protocol, Alice the sender has two messages *m*0 and *m*1, and wants to ensure that the receiver only learns one.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Bob, the receiver, has a bit *b* and wishes to receive *m**b* without Alice learning *b*.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The protocol of Even, Goldreich, and Lempel (which the authors attribute partially to Silvio Micali) is general, but can be instantiated using RSA encryption as follows.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Alice generates an RSA key pair, comprising the modulus N , the public exponent e and the private exponent d .
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] She also generates two random values, $x_{0},x_{1}$ , and sends them to Bob along with her public modulus and exponent.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Bob picks b to be either 0 or 1 and selects $x_{b}$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Bob generates a random value k and uses it to blind $x_{b}$ by computing $v=(x_{b}+k^{e}){\bmod {N}}$ , which he sends to Alice.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Now $k_{b}$ will be equal to $k,$ and the other will be a meaningless random value.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] However, since Alice does not know the value of b that Bob chose, she cannot determine which of $k_{0}$ and $k_{1}$ is equal to k .
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] A 1-out-of-*n* oblivious transfer protocol can be defined as a natural generalization of a 1-out-of-2 oblivious transfer protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Specifically, a sender has *n* messages, and the receiver has an index *i*, and the receiver wishes to receive the *i*-th among the sender's messages, without the sender learning *i*, while the sender wants to ensure that the receiver receive only one of the *n* messages.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] 1-out-of-*n* oblivious transfer is incomparable to private information retrieval (PIR).
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] On the one hand, 1-out-of-*n* oblivious transfer imposes an additional privacy requirement for the database: namely, that the receiver learn at most one of the database entries.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] On the other hand, PIR requires communication sublinear in *n*, whereas 1-out-of-*n* oblivious transfer has no such requirement.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] However, assuming single server PIR is a sufficient assumption in order to construct 1-out-of-2 Oblivious Transfer.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] 1-out-of-*n* oblivious transfer protocol with sublinear communication was first constructed (as a generalization of single-server PIR) by Eyal Kushilevitz and Rafail Ostrovsky.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] More efficient constructions were proposed by Moni Naor and Benny Pinkas, William Aiello, Yuval Ishai and Omer Reingold, Sven Laur and Helger Lipmaa.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In 2017, Kolesnikov et al., proposed an efficient 1-n oblivious transfer protocol which requires roughly 4x the cost of 1-2 oblivious transfer in amortized setting.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Brassard, Crépeau and Robert further generalized this notion to *k*-*n* oblivious transfer, wherein the receiver obtains a set of *k* messages from the *n* message collection.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] The set of *k* messages may be received simultaneously ("non-adaptively"), or they may be requested consecutively, with each request based on previous messages received.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] In the early seventies Stephen Wiesner introduced a primitive called **multiplexing** in his seminal paper "Conjugate Coding", which was the starting point of quantum cryptography.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Unfortunately it took more than ten years to be published.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Even though this primitive was equivalent to what was later called *1–2 oblivious transfer*, Wiesner did not see its application to cryptography.
[src:secure-aggregation/oblivious-transfer] Protocols for oblivious transfer can be implemented with quantum systems.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In one type of secret sharing scheme there is one *dealer* and *n* *players*.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The dealer gives a share of the secret to the players, but only when specific conditions are fulfilled will the players be able to reconstruct the secret from their shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The dealer accomplishes this by giving each player a share in such a way that any group of *t* (for *threshold*) or more players can together reconstruct the secret but no group of fewer than *t* players can.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Such a system is called a (*t*, *n*)-threshold scheme (sometimes it is written as an (*n*, *t*)-threshold scheme).
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing was invented independently by Adi Shamir and George Blakley in 1979.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are ideal for storing information that is highly sensitive and highly important.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Examples include: encryption keys, missile launch codes, and numbered bank accounts.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Each of these pieces of information must be kept highly confidential, as their exposure could be disastrous; however, it is also critical that they should not be lost.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Traditional methods for encryption are ill-suited for simultaneously achieving high levels of confidentiality and reliability.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This is because when storing the encryption key, one must choose between keeping a single copy of the key in one location for maximum secrecy, or keeping multiple copies of the key in different locations for greater reliability.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Increasing reliability of the key by storing multiple copies lowers confidentiality by creating additional attack vectors; there are more opportunities for a copy to fall into the wrong hands.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes address this problem, and allow arbitrarily high levels of confidentiality and reliability to be achieved.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing also allows the distributor of the secret to trust a group 'in aggregate'.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Traditionally, giving a secret to a group for safekeeping would require that the distributor completely trust all members of the group.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes allow the distributor to securely store the secret with the group even if not all members can be trusted all the time.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] So long as the number of traitors is never more than the critical number needed to reconstruct the secret, the secret is safe.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are important in cloud computing environments.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Thus a key can be distributed over many servers by a threshold secret sharing mechanism.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The key is then reconstructed when needed.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing has also been suggested for sensor networks where the links are liable to be tapped, by sending the data in shares which makes the task of the eavesdropper harder.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The security in such environments can be made greater by continuous changing of the way the shares are constructed.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A secure secret sharing scheme distributes shares so that anyone with fewer than *t* shares has no more information about the secret than someone with 0 shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Consider for example the secret sharing scheme in which the secret phrase "password" is divided into the shares "pa––––––", "––ss––––", "––––wo––", and "––––––rd".
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A person with 0 shares knows only that the password consists of eight letters, and thus would have to guess the password from 268 = 208 billion possible combinations.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A person with one share, however, would have to guess only the six letters, from 266 = 308 million combinations, and so on as more persons collude.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Consequently, this system is not a "secure" secret sharing scheme, because a player with fewer than *t* secret shares is able to reduce the problem of obtaining the inner secret without first needing to obtain all of the necessary shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In contrast, consider the secret sharing scheme where *X* is the secret to be shared, *Pi* are public asymmetric encryption keys and *Qi* their corresponding private keys.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any player with private key 1 can remove the outer layer of encryption, a player with keys 1 and 2 can remove the first and second layer, and so on.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A player with fewer than *N* keys can never fully reach the secret *X* without first needing to decrypt a public-key-encrypted blob for which he does not have the corresponding private key – a problem that is currently believed to be computationally infeasible.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Additionally we can see that any user with all *N* private keys is able to decrypt all of the outer layers to obtain *X*, the secret, and consequently this system is a secure secret distribution system.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Several secret-sharing schemes are said to be information-theoretically secure and can be proven to be so, while others give up this *unconditional security* for improved efficiency while maintaining enough security to be considered as secure as other common cryptographic primitives.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] For example, they might allow secrets to be protected by shares with entropy of 128 bits each, since each share would be considered enough to stymie any conceivable present-day adversary, requiring a brute force attack of average size 2127.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Note: *n* is the total number of 'players', among whom the shares are distributed, and *t* is the minimum number of players required to reveal the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Instead, (1) can be performed using the binary operation in any group.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] For example, take the cyclic group of integers with addition modulo 232, which corresponds to 32-bit integers with addition defined with the binary overflow being discarded.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The secret *s* can be partitioned into a vector of *M* 32-bit integers, which we call *v*secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Then (*n* − 1) of the players are each given a vector of *M* 32-bit integers that is drawn independently from a uniform probability distribution, with player *i* receiving *vi*.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The secret vector can then be recovered by summing across all the players' vectors.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The difficulty lies in creating schemes that are still secure, but do not require all *n* shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] When space efficiency is not a concern, trivial *t* = *n* schemes can be used to reveal a secret to any desired subsets of the players simply by applying the scheme for each subset.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] For example, to reveal a secret *s* to any two of the three players Alice, Bob and Carol, create three ( ${\binom {3}{2}}$ ) different *t* = *n* = 2 secret shares for *s*, giving the three sets of two shares to Alice and Bob, Alice and Carol, and Bob and Carol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] For example, imagine that the board of directors of a company would like to protect their secret formula.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The president of the company should be able to access the formula when needed, but in an emergency any 3 of the 12 board members would be able to unlock the secret formula together.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] One of the ways this can be accomplished is by a secret-sharing scheme with *t* = 3 and *n* = 15, where 3 shares are given to the president, and one share is given to each board member.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In the worst case, the increase is exponential.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This has led to the search for schemes that allow secrets to be shared efficiently with a threshold of players.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A ramp secret sharing scheme is a secret-sharing scheme with two thresholds: groups below the lower threshold learn no information about the secret, groups at or above the upper threshold can reconstruct it, and intermediate-size groups may obtain partial information.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This relaxation can reduce the size of shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Hirosuke Yamamoto's (*k*, *L*, *n*) threshold scheme is an early information-theoretic formulation of this trade-off.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any *t* out of *n* shares may be used to recover the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The system relies on the idea that one can construct a unique polynomial of degree *t* − 1, such that each of the *t* points lies on the polynomial.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] It takes two points to define a straight line, three points to fully define a quadratic, four points to define a cubic curve, and so on.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] That is, it takes *t* points to define a polynomial of degree *t* − 1.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The method is to create a polynomial of degree *t* − 1 with the secret as the first coefficient and the remaining coefficients picked at random.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Next find *n* points on the curve and give one to each of the players.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] When at least *t* out of the *n* players reveal their points, there is sufficient information to fit a (*t* − 1)th degree polynomial to them, the first coefficient being the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] , and the secret is the point at which three shares intersect.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Two nonparallel lines in the same plane intersect at exactly one point.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Three nonparallel planes in space intersect at exactly one point.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] More generally, any *n* nonparallel (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes intersect at a specific point.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The secret may be encoded as any single coordinate of the point of intersection.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] If the secret is encoded using all the coordinates, even if they are random, then an insider (someone in possession of one or more of the (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes) gains information about the secret since he knows it must lie on his plane.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] If an insider can gain any more knowledge about the secret than an outsider can, then the system no longer has information theoretic security.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] If only one of the *n* coordinates is used, then the insider knows no more than an outsider (i.e., that the secret must lie on the *x*-axis for a 2-dimensional system).
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Each player is given enough information to define a hyperplane; the secret is recovered by calculating the planes' point of intersection and then taking a specified coordinate of that intersection.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme is less space-efficient than Shamir's; while Shamir's shares are each only as large as the original secret, Blakley's shares are *t* times larger, where *t* is the threshold number of players.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme can be tightened by adding restrictions on which planes are usable as shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The resulting scheme is equivalent to Shamir's polynomial system.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The Chinese remainder theorem can also be used in secret sharing, for it provides us with a method to uniquely determine a number *S* modulo *k* many pairwise coprime integers $m_{1},m_{2},...,m_{k}$ , given that $S<\prod _{i=1}^{k}m_{i}$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] There are two secret sharing schemes that make use of the Chinese remainder theorem, Mignotte's and Asmuth-Bloom's Schemes.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] They are threshold secret sharing schemes, in which the shares are generated by reduction modulo the integers $m_{i}$ , and the secret is recovered by essentially solving the system of congruences using the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] If the players store their shares on insecure computer servers, an attacker could crack in and steal the shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] If it is not practical to change the secret, the uncompromised (Shamir-style) shares can be renewed.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The dealer generates a new random polynomial with constant term zero and calculates for each remaining player a new ordered pair, where the x-coordinates of the old and new pairs are the same.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Each player then adds the old and new y-coordinates to each other and keeps the result as the new y-coordinate of the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] All of the non-updated shares the attacker accumulated become useless.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] An attacker can only recover the secret if he can find enough other non-updated shares to reach the threshold.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This situation should not happen because the players deleted their old shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Additionally, an attacker cannot recover any information about the original secret from the update files because they contain only random information.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The dealer can change the threshold number while distributing updates, but must always remain vigilant of players keeping expired shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A player might lie about his own share to gain access to other shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A *verifiable secret sharing* (VSS) scheme allows players to be certain that no other players are lying about the contents of their shares, up to a reasonable probability of error.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Such schemes cannot be computed conventionally; the players must collectively add and multiply numbers without any individual's knowing what exactly is being added and multiplied.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The disadvantage of unconditionally secure secret sharing schemes is that the storage and transmission of the shares requires an amount of storage and bandwidth resources equivalent to the size of the secret times the number of shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] If the size of the secret were significant, say 1 GB, and the number of shares were 10, then 10 GB of data must be stored by the shareholders.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Alternate techniques have been proposed for greatly increasing the efficiency of secret sharing schemes, by giving up the requirement of unconditional security.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] One of these techniques, known as *secret sharing made short*, combines Rabin's information dispersal algorithm (IDA) with Shamir's secret sharing.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Data is first encrypted with a randomly generated key, using a symmetric encryption algorithm.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Next this data is split into N pieces using Rabin's IDA.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This IDA is configured with a threshold, in a manner similar to secret sharing schemes, but unlike secret sharing schemes the size of the resulting data grows by a factor of (number of fragments / threshold).
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] For example, if the threshold were 10, and the number of IDA-produced fragments were 15, the total size of all the fragments would be (15/10) or 1.5 times the size of the original input.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In this case, this scheme is 10 times more efficient than if Shamir's scheme had been applied directly on the data.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The final step in secret sharing made short is to use Shamir secret sharing to produce shares of the randomly generated symmetric key (which is typically on the order of 16–32 bytes) and then give one share and one fragment to each shareholder.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A related approach, known as AONT-RS, applies an All-or-nothing transform to the data as a pre-processing step to an IDA.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The All-or-nothing transform guarantees that any number of shares less than the threshold is insufficient to decrypt the data.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] An information-theoretically secure *k*-of-*n* secret-sharing scheme generates *n* shares, each of size at least that of the secret itself, leading to the total required storage being at least *n*-fold larger than the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In multi-secret sharing designed by Matthew K.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Franklin and Moti Yung, multiple points of the polynomial host secrets; the method was found useful in numerous applications from coding to multi-party computations.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In space efficient secret sharing, devised by Abhishek Parakh and Subhash Kak, each share is roughly the size of the secret divided by *k* − 1.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This scheme makes use of repeated polynomial interpolation and has potential applications in secure information dispersal on the Web and in sensor networks.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This method is based on data partitioning involving the roots of a polynomial in finite field.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Some vulnerabilities of related *space efficient* secret sharing schemes were pointed out later.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] They show that a scheme based on interpolation method cannot be used to implement a (*k*, *n*) scheme when the *k* secrets to be distributed are inherently generated from a polynomial of degree less than *k* − 1, and the scheme does not work if all of the secrets to be shared are the same, etc.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A secret-sharing scheme can secure a secret over multiple servers and remain recoverable despite multiple server failures.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] The dealer may act as several distinct participants, distributing the shares among the participants.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This is one of the major concepts behind the Vanish computer project at the University of Washington, where a random key is used to encrypt data, and the key is distributed as a secret across several nodes in a P2P network.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] In order to decrypt the message, at least *t* nodes on the network must be accessible; the principle for this particular project being that the number of secret-sharing nodes on the network will decrease naturally over time, therefore causing the secret to eventually *vanish*.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] However, the network is vulnerable to a Sybil attack, thus making Vanish insecure.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Any shareholder who ever has enough information to decrypt the content at any point is able to take and store a copy of X.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Consequently, although tools and techniques such as Vanish can make data irrecoverable within their own system after a time, it is not possible to force the deletion of data once a malicious user has seen it.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] This is one of the leading conundrums of digital rights management.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] A dealer could send *t* shares, all of which are necessary to recover the original secret, to a single recipient.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] An attacker would have to intercept all *t* shares to recover the secret, a task which is more difficult than intercepting a single file, especially if the shares are sent using different media (e.g. some over the Internet, some mailed on CDs).
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] For large secrets, it may be more efficient to encrypt the secret and then distribute the key using secret sharing.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing is an important primitive in several protocols for secure multiparty computation.
[src:secure-aggregation/secret-sharing] Secret sharing can also be used for user authentication in a system.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The foundation for secure multi-party computation started in the late 1970s with the work on mental poker, cryptographic work that simulates game playing/computational tasks over distances without requiring a trusted third party.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Traditionally, cryptography was about concealing content, while this new type of computation and protocol is about concealing partial information about data while computing with the data from many sources, and correctly producing outputs.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] By the late 1980s, Michael Ben-Or, Shafi Goldwasser and Avi Wigderson, and independently David Chaum, Claude Crépeau, and Ivan Damgård, had published papers showing "how to securely compute any function in the secure channels setting".
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Special purpose protocols for specific tasks started in the late 1970s.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Later, secure computation was formally introduced as secure two-party computation (2PC) in 1982 (for the so-called Millionaires' Problem, a specific problem which is a Boolean predicate), and in generality (for any feasible computation) in 1986 by Andrew Yao.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The area is also referred to as Secure Function Evaluation (SFE).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The two party case was followed by a generalization to the multi-party by Oded Goldreich, Silvio Micali, and Avi Wigderson.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This work suggested the very basic general scheme to be followed by essentially all future multi-party protocols for secure computing.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This work introduced an approach, known as GMW paradigm, for compiling a multi-party computation protocol which is secure against semi-honest adversaries to a protocol that is secure against malicious adversaries.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This work was followed by the first robust secure protocol which tolerates faulty behavior graciously without revealing anyone's output via a work which invented for this purpose the often used `share of shares idea' and a protocol that allows one of the parties to hide its input unconditionally.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The GMW paradigm was considered to be inefficient for years because of huge overheads that it brings to the base protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] However, it is shown that it is possible to achieve efficient protocols, and it makes this line of research even more interesting from a practical perspective.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The above results are in a model where the adversary is limited to polynomial time computations, and it observes all communications, and therefore the model is called the `computational model'.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Further, the protocol of oblivious transfer was shown to be complete for these tasks.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The above results established that it is possible under the above variations to achieve secure computation when the majority of users are honest.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Adding a broadcast channel allows the system to tolerate up to 1/2 misbehaving minority, whereas connectivity constraints on the communication graph were investigated in the book Perfectly Secure Message Transmission.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Over the years, the notion of general purpose multi-party protocols became a fertile area to investigate basic and general protocol issues properties on, such as universal composability or mobile adversary as in proactive secret sharing.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Since the late 2000s, and certainly since 2010 and on, the domain of general purpose protocols has moved to deal with efficiency improvements of the protocols with practical applications in mind.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The first large-scale and practical application of multi-party computation was the execution of an electronic double auction in the Danish Sugar Beet Auction, which took place in January 2008.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Obviously, both theoretical notions and investigations, and applied constructions are needed (e.g., conditions for moving MPC into part of day by day business was advocated and presented in).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In an MPC, a given number of participants, p1, p2, ..., pN, each have private data, respectively d1, d2, ..., dN.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Participants want to compute the value of a public function on that private data: F(d1, d2, ..., dN) while keeping their own inputs secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] For example, suppose we have three parties Alice, Bob and Charlie, with respective inputs x, y and z denoting their salaries.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] They want to find out the highest of the three salaries, without revealing to each other how much each of them makes.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] If there were some trusted outside party (say, they had a mutual friend Tony who they knew could keep a secret), they could each tell their salary to Tony, he could compute the maximum, and tell that number to all of them.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The goal of MPC is to design a protocol, where, by exchanging messages only with each other, Alice, Bob, and Charlie can still learn F(x, y, z) without revealing who makes what and without having to rely on Tony.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] They should learn no more by engaging in their protocol than they would learn by interacting with an incorruptible, perfectly trustworthy Tony.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In particular, all that the parties can learn is what they can learn from the output and their own input.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] So in the above example, if the output is z, then Charlie learns that his z is the maximum value, whereas Alice and Bob learn (if x, y and z are distinct), that their input is not equal to the maximum, and that the maximum held is equal to z.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The basic scenario can be easily generalised to where the parties have several inputs and outputs, and the function outputs different values to different parties.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] There are a wide range of practical applications, varying from simple tasks such as coin tossing to more complex ones like electronic auctions (e.g. compute the market clearing price), electronic voting, or privacy-preserving data mining.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A classical example is the Millionaires' Problem: two millionaires want to know who is richer, in such a way that neither of them learns the net worth of the other.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A solution to this situation is essentially to securely evaluate the comparison function.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A multi-party computation protocol must be secure to be effective.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In modern cryptography, the security of a protocol is related to a security proof.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The security proof is a mathematical proof where the security of a protocol is reduced to that of the security of its underlying primitives.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Nevertheless, it is not always possible to formalize the cryptographic protocol security verification based on the party knowledge and the protocol correctness.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] For MPC protocols, the environment in which the protocol operates is associated with the Real World/Ideal World Paradigm.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The parties can't be said to learn nothing, since they need to learn the output of the operation, and the output depends on the inputs.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In addition, the output correctness is not guaranteed, since the correctness of the output depends on the parties’ inputs, and the inputs have to be assumed to be correct.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The Real World/Ideal World Paradigm states two worlds: (i) In the ideal-world model, there exists an incorruptible trusted party to whom each protocol participant sends its input.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This trusted party computes the function on its own and sends back the appropriate output to each party.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] (ii) In contrast, in the real-world model, there is no trusted party and all the parties can do is to exchange messages with each other.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A protocol is said to be secure if one can learn no more about each party's private inputs in the real world than one could learn in the ideal world.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In the ideal world, no messages are exchanged between parties, so real-world exchanged messages cannot reveal any secret information.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The Real World/Ideal World Paradigm provides a simple abstraction of the complexities of MPC to allow the construction of an application under the pretense that the MPC protocol at its core is actually an ideal execution.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] If the application is secure in the ideal case, then it is also secure when a real protocol is run instead.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The security requirements on an MPC protocol are stringent.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Nonetheless, in 1987 it was demonstrated that any function can be securely computed, with security for malicious adversaries and the other initial works mentioned before.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Despite these publications, MPC was not designed to be efficient enough to be used in practice at that time.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Unconditionally or information-theoretically secure MPC is closely related and builds on to the problem of secret sharing, and more specifically verifiable secret sharing (VSS), which many secure MPC protocols use against active adversaries.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Unlike traditional cryptographic applications, such as encryption or signature, one must assume that the adversary in an MPC protocol is one of the players engaged in the system (or controlling internal parties).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] That corrupted party or parties may collude in order to breach the security of the protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Let n be the number of parties in the protocol and t the number of parties who can be adversarial.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The protocols and solutions for the case of $t<n/2$ (i.e., when an honest majority is assumed) are different from those where no such assumption is made.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This latter case includes the important case of two-party computation where one of the participants may be corrupted, and the general case where an unlimited number of participants are corrupted and collude to attack the honest participants.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Adversaries faced by the different protocols can be categorized according to how willing they are to deviate from the protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Security against active adversaries typically leads to a reduction in efficiency.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Covert security is an alternative that aims to allow greater efficiency in exchange for weakening the security definition; it is applicable to situations where active adversaries are willing to cheat but only if they are not caught.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] For example, their reputation could be damaged, preventing future collaboration with other honest parties.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Thus, protocols that are covertly secure provide mechanisms to ensure that, if some of the parties do not follow the instructions, then it will be noticed with high probability, say 75% or 90%.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In a way, covert adversaries are active ones forced to act passively due to external non-cryptographic (e.g. business) concerns.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This mechanism sets a bridge between both models in the hope of finding protocols which are efficient and secure enough in practice.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The set of honest parties that can execute a computational task is related to the concept of access structure.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Adversary structures can be static, where the adversary chooses its victims before the start of the multi-party computation, or dynamic, where it chooses its victims during the course of execution of the multi-party computation making the defense harder.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] An adversary structure can be defined as a threshold structure or as a more complex structure.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In a threshold structure the adversary can corrupt or read the memory of a number of participants up to some threshold.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Meanwhile, in a complex structure it can affect certain predefined subsets of participants, modeling different possible collusions.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] There are major differences between the protocols proposed for two party computation (2PC) and multi-party computation (MPC).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The two party setting is particularly interesting, not only from an applications perspective but also because special techniques can be applied in the two party setting which do not apply in the multi-party case.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Indeed, secure multi-party computation (in fact the restricted case of secure function evaluation, where only a single function is evaluated) was first presented in the two-party setting.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The original work is often cited as being from one of the two papers of Yao; although the papers do not actually contain what is now known as Yao's garbled circuit protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Yao's basic protocol is secure against semi-honest adversaries and is extremely efficient in terms of number of rounds, which is constant, and independent of the target function being evaluated.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The function is viewed as a Boolean circuit, with inputs in binary of fixed length.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A Boolean circuit is a collection of gates connected with three different types of wires: circuit-input wires, circuit-output wires and intermediate wires.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Each gate receives two input wires and it has a single output wire which might be fan-out (i.e. be passed to multiple gates at the next level).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Plain evaluation of the circuit is done by evaluating each gate in turn; assuming the gates have been topologically ordered.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The gate is represented as a truth table such that for each possible pair of bits (those coming from the input wires' gate) the table assigns a unique output bit; which is the value of the output wire of the gate.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The results of the evaluation are the bits obtained in the circuit-output wires.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Yao explained how to garble a circuit (hide its structure) so that two parties, sender and receiver, can learn the output of the circuit and nothing else.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] At a high level, the sender prepares the garbled circuit and sends it to the receiver, who obliviously evaluates the circuit, learning the encodings corresponding to both his and the sender's output.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] He then just sends back the sender's encodings, allowing the sender to compute his part of the output.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The sender sends the mapping from the receivers output encodings to bits to the receiver, allowing the receiver to obtain their output.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In more detail, the garbled circuit is computed as follows.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The main ingredient is a double-keyed symmetric encryption scheme.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Given a gate of the circuit, each possible value of its input wires (either 0 or 1) is encoded with a random number (label).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The values resulting from the evaluation of the gate at each of the four possible pair of input bits are also replaced with random labels.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The garbled truth table of the gate consists of encryptions of each output label using its inputs labels as keys.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The position of these four encryptions in the truth table is randomized so no information on the gate is leaked.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] To correctly evaluate each garbled gate the encryption scheme has the following two properties.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Firstly, the ranges of the encryption function under any two distinct keys are disjoint (with overwhelming probability).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The second property says that it can be checked efficiently whether a given ciphertext has been encrypted under a given key.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] With these two properties the receiver, after obtaining the labels for all circuit-input wires, can evaluate each gate by first finding out which of the four ciphertexts has been encrypted with his label keys, and then decrypting to obtain the label of the output wire.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This is done obliviously as all the receiver learns during the evaluation are encodings of the bits.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The sender's (i.e. circuit creators) input bits can be just sent as encodings to the evaluator; whereas the receiver's (i.e. circuit evaluators) encodings corresponding to his input bits are obtained via a 1-out-of-2 oblivious transfer (OT) protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A 1-out-of-2 OT protocol enables the sender possessing of two values C1 and C2 to send the one requested by the receiver (b a value in {1,2}) in such a way that the sender does not know what value has been transferred, and the receiver only learns the queried value.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] If one is considering malicious adversaries, further mechanisms to ensure correct behavior of both parties need to be provided.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] By construction it is easy to show security for the sender if the OT protocol is already secure against malicious adversary, as all the receiver can do is to evaluate a garbled circuit that would fail to reach the circuit-output wires if he deviated from the instructions.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The situation is very different on the sender's side.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] For example, he may send an incorrect garbled circuit that computes a function revealing the receiver's input.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This would mean that privacy no longer holds, but since the circuit is garbled the receiver would not be able to detect this.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] However, it is possible to efficiently apply Zero-Knowledge proofs to make this protocol secure against malicious adversaries with a small overhead comparing to the semi-honest protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Most MPC protocols, as opposed to 2PC protocols and especially under the unconditional setting of private channels, make use of secret sharing.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In the secret sharing based methods, the parties do not play special roles (as in Yao, of creator and evaluator).
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Instead, the data associated with each wire is shared amongst the parties, and a protocol is then used to evaluate each gate.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The function is now defined as a "circuit" over a finite field, as opposed to the binary circuits used for Yao.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Such a circuit is called an arithmetic circuit in the literature, and it consists of addition and multiplication "gates" where the values operated on are defined over a finite field.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Secret sharing allows one to distribute a secret among a number of parties by distributing shares to each party.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Two types of secret sharing schemes are commonly used; Shamir secret sharing and additive secret sharing.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In both cases the shares are random elements of a finite field that add up to the secret in the field; intuitively, security is achieved because any non-qualifying set of shares looks randomly distributed.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Secret sharing schemes can tolerate an adversary controlling up to *t* parties out of *n* total parties, where *t* varies based on the scheme, the adversary can be passive or active, and different assumptions are made on the power of the adversary.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The BGW protocol, which defines how to compute addition and multiplication on secret shares, is often used to compute functions with Shamir secret shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Additive secret sharing schemes can tolerate the adversary controlling all but one party, that is $t<n$ , while maintaining security against a passive and active adversary with unbounded computational power.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Some protocols require a setup phase, which may only be secure against a computationally bounded adversary.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] A number of systems have implemented various forms of MPC with secret sharing schemes.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The most popular is SPDZ, which implements MPC with additive secret shares and is secure against active adversaries.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In 2014 a "model of fairness in secure computation in which an adversarial party that aborts on receiving output is forced to pay a mutually predefined monetary penalty" has been described for the Bitcoin network or for fair lottery, and has been successfully implemented in Ethereum.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Many advances have been made on 2PC and MPC systems in recent years.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In 2025, the company Partisia, which is co-founded by Ivan Damgård, demonstrated several practical applications of MPC in the field of digital identity and privacy.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In collaboration with Toppan and the Okinawa Institute of Science and Technology, Partisia ran a proof-of-concept in Japan using facial recognition and decentralized identifiers to build a privacy-preserving student ID system compliant with eIDAS 2.0 standards.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The system matched biometric data using MPC without decrypting it, allowing verification while maintaining full privacy.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Partisia also partnered with entities in Denmark, Colombia, and the United States to apply MPC in healthcare analytics, cross-border digital identity, and secure banking data exchange.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] One of the main issues when working with Yao-based protocols is that the function to be securely evaluated (which could be an arbitrary program) must be represented as a circuit, usually consisting of XOR and AND gates.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Since most real-world programs contain loops and complex data structures, this is a highly non-trivial task.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The Fairplay system was the first tool designed to tackle this problem.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The first of these is a compiler enabling users to write programs in a simple high-level language, and output these programs in a Boolean circuit representation.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The second component can then garble the circuit and execute a protocol to securely evaluate the garbled circuit.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] As well as two-party computation based on Yao's protocol, Fairplay can also carry out multi-party protocols.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This is done using the BMR protocol, which extends Yao's passively secure protocol to the active case.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In the years following the introduction of Fairplay, many improvements to Yao's basic protocol have been created, in the form of both efficiency improvements and techniques for active security.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] These include techniques such as the free XOR method, which allows for much simpler evaluation of XOR gates, and garbled row reduction, reducing the size of garbled tables with two inputs by 25%.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The approach that so far seems to be the most fruitful in obtaining active security comes from a combination of the garbling technique and the "cut-and-choose" paradigm.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This combination seems to render more efficient constructions.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] To avoid the aforementioned problems with respect to dishonest behaviour, many garblings of the same circuit are sent from the constructor to the evaluator.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Then around half of them (depending on the specific protocol) are opened to check consistency, and if so a vast majority of the unopened ones are correct with high probability.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The output is the majority vote of all the evaluations.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] If there is disagreement on the outputs the receiver knows the sender is cheating, but he cannot complain as otherwise this would leak information on his input.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This approach for active security was initiated by Lindell and Pinkas.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] As many circuits are evaluated, the parties (including the receiver) need to commit to their inputs to ensure that in all the iterations the same values are used.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The experiments of Pinkas et al. reported show that the bottleneck of the protocol lies in the consistency checks.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] They had to send over the net about 6,553,600 commitments to various values to evaluate the AES circuit.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In recent results the efficiency of actively secure Yao-based implementations was improved even further, requiring only 40 circuits, and a much smaller number of commitments, to obtain $2^{-40}$ cheating probability.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The improvements come from new methodologies for performing cut-and-choose on the transmitted circuits.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] More recently, there has been a focus on highly parallel implementations based on garbled circuits, designed to be run on CPUs with many cores.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Kreuter, et al. describe an implementation running on 512 cores of a powerful cluster computer.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Using these resources they could evaluate the 4095-bit edit distance function, whose circuit comprises almost 6 billion gates.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] To accomplish this they developed a custom, better optimized circuit compiler than Fairplay and several new optimizations such as pipelining, whereby transmission of the garbled circuit across the network begins while the rest of the circuit is still being generated.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The time to compute AES was reduced to 1.4 seconds per block in the active case, using a 512-node cluster machine, and 115 seconds using one node.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Shelat and Shen improve this, using commodity hardware, to 0.52 seconds per block.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The same paper reports on a throughput of 21 blocks per second, but with a latency of 48 seconds per block.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] Meanwhile, another group of researchers has investigated using consumer-grade GPUs to achieve similar levels of parallelism.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] They utilize oblivious transfer extensions and some other novel techniques to design their GPU-specific protocol.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] This approach seems to achieve comparable efficiency to the cluster computing implementation, using a similar number of cores.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] However, the authors only report on an implementation of the AES circuit, which has around 50,000 gates.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] On the other hand, the hardware required here is far more accessible, as similar devices may already be found in many people's desktop computers or games consoles.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] The authors obtain a timing of 2.7 seconds per AES block on a standard desktop, with a standard GPU.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] If they allow security to decrease to something akin to covert security, they obtain a run time of 0.30 seconds per AES block.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] In the passive security case there are reports of processing of circuits with 250 million gates, and at a rate of 75 million gates per second.
[src:secure-aggregation/secure-multi-party-computation] One of the primary applications of secure multi-party computation is allowing analysis of data that is held by multiple parties, or blind analysis of data by third parties without allowing the data custodian to understand the kind of data analysis being performed.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Shamir's secret sharing is used in some applications to share the access keys to a master secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] SSS is used to secure a secret in a distributed form, most often to secure encryption keys.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The secret is split into multiple shares, which individually do not give any information about the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] To reconstruct a secret secured by SSS, a number of shares is needed, called the *threshold*.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] No information about the secret can be gained from any number of shares below the threshold (a property called perfect secrecy).
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] In this sense, SSS is a generalisation of the one-time pad (which can be viewed as SSS with a two-share threshold and two shares in total).
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] If a *single* person knows the code to the vault, the code might be lost or unavailable when the vault needs to be opened.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] If there are *several* people who know the code, they may not trust each other to always act honestly.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] SSS can be used in this situation to generate shares of the vault's code which are distributed to authorized individuals in the company.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The minimum threshold and number of shares given to each individual can be selected such that the vault is accessible only by (groups of) authorized individuals.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] If fewer shares than the threshold are presented, the vault cannot be opened.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] By accident, coercion or as an act of opposition, some individuals might present incorrect information for their shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] If the total of correct shares fails to meet the minimum threshold, the vault remains locked.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] SSS has useful properties, but also weaknesses that means that it is unsuited to some uses.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] **Minimal**: The size of each piece does not exceed the size of the original data.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] **Dynamic**: Security can be enhanced without changing the secret, but by changing the polynomial occasionally (keeping the same free term) and constructing a new share for each of the participants.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] **Flexible**: In organizations where hierarchy is important, each participant can be issued different numbers of shares according to their importance inside the organization.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] For instance, with a *threshold* of 3, the president could unlock the safe alone if given three shares, while three secretaries with one share each must combine their shares to unlock the safe.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] **Single point of failure**: The secret must exist in one place when it is split into shares, and again in one place when it is reassembled.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] These are attack points, and other schemes including multisignature eliminate at least one of these single points of failure.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Adi Shamir first formulated the scheme in 1979.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The scheme exploits the Lagrange interpolation theorem, specifically that k points on the polynomial uniquely determines a polynomial of degree less than or equal to $k-1$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] For instance, 2 points are sufficient to define a line, 3 points are sufficient to define a parabola, 4 points to define a cubic curve and so forth.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Shamir's secret sharing is an ideal and perfect $\left(k,n\right)$ -*threshold scheme* based on polynomial interpolation over finite fields.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Knowledge of any $k-1$ or fewer shares $S_{i}$ leaves S completely undetermined, in the sense that the possible values for S remain as likely with knowledge of up to $k-1$ shares as with knowledge of 0 shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The secret S cannot be reconstructed with fewer than k shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] If $n=k$ , then all of the shares are needed to reconstruct the secret S .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Assume that the secret S can be represented as an element $a_{0}$ of a finite field $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ (where q is greater than the number n of shares being generated).
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Compute any n points out on the curve, for instance set $i=1,\ldots ,n$ to find points $\left(i,f\left(i\right)\right)$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Every participant is given a point (a non-zero input to the polynomial, and the corresponding output).
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Note that $f(0)$ is equal to the first coefficient of polynomial $f(x)$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] More generally, any value $f(\alpha )$ , where $\alpha \in \mathrm {GF} (q)$ , may be used as the secret instead of $f(0)$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The leading coefficient $a_{k-1}$ may similarly be interpreted as the value $f(\infty )$ on the projective line and can also be used as the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] These are precisely the polynomial-derived quantities that remain perfectly hidden from every coalition of fewer than k participants.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] In contrast, other linear combinations of the polynomial coefficients, including the intermediate coefficients, $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{k-2}$ , may be determined by some coalitions of fewer than k participants.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The following example illustrates the basic idea.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Note, however, that calculations in the example are done using integer arithmetic rather than using finite field arithmetic to make the idea easier to understand.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Therefore, the example below does not provide perfect secrecy and is not a proper example of Shamir's scheme.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The next example will explain the problem.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Suppose that the secret to be shared is 1234 $(S=1234)$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] In this example, the secret will be split into 6 shares $(n=6)$ , where any subset of 3 shares $(k=3)$ is sufficient to reconstruct the secret. $k-1=2$ numbers are taken at random.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Each participant in the scheme receives a different point (a pair of x and $f(x)$ ).
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] This is necessary because $f(0)$ is the secret.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Recalling that the secret is the free coefficient, which means that $S=1234$ , and the secret has been recovered.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Using polynomial interpolation to find a coefficient in a source polynomial $S=f(0)$ using Lagrange polynomials is not efficient, since unused constants are calculated.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Although the simplified version of the method demonstrated above, which uses integer arithmetic rather than finite field arithmetic, works, there is a security problem: Eve gains information about S with every $D_{i}$ that she finds.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Suppose that she finds the point $D=(2,1942)$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] She still does not have $k=3$ points, so in theory she should not have gained any more information about S .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] which leads her to the information that S is even.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The above attack exploits constraints on the values that the polynomial may take by virtue of how it was constructed: the polynomial must have coefficients that are integers, and the polynomial must take an integer as value when evaluated at each of the coordinates used in the scheme.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] This reduces its possible values at unknown points, including the resultant secret, given fewer than k shares.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] This problem can be remedied by using finite field arithmetic.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] A finite field always has size $q=p^{r}$ , where p is a prime and r is a positive integer.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The size q of the field must satisfy $q>n$ , and that q is greater than the number of possible values for the secret, though the latter condition may be circumvented by splitting the secret into smaller secret values, and applying the scheme to each of these.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] In our example below, we use a prime field (i.e.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The figure shows a polynomial curve over a finite field.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] In practice this is only a small change.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The order *q* of the field (i.e. the number of values that it has) must be chosen to be greater than the number of participants and the number of values that the secret $a_{0}=S$ may take.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] All calculations involving the polynomial must also be calculated over the field (mod *p* in our example, in which $p=q$ is taken to be a prime) instead of over the integers.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Both the choice of the field and the mapping of the secret to a value in this field are considered to be publicly known.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] This time Eve doesn't gain any information when she finds a $D_{x}$ (until she has k points).
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] There are p possible values for $a_{1}$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] She knows that $[448,445,442,\ldots ]$ always decreases by 3, so if p were divisible by 3 she could conclude $a_{1}\in [1,4,7,\ldots ]$ .
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] However, p is prime, so she can not conclude this.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Thus, using a finite field avoids this possible attack.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] Also, even though Eve can conclude that $S\equiv 1046+2a_{2}{\pmod {1613}}$ , it does not provide any additional information, since the "wrapping around" behavior of modular arithmetic prevents the leakage of "S is even", unlike the example with integer arithmetic above.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] For purposes of keeping the code clearer, a prime field is used here.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] In practice, for convenience a scheme constructed using a smaller binary field may be separately applied to small substrings of bits of the secret (e.g.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] GF(256) for byte-wise application, where GF is Galois Field), without loss of security.
[src:secure-aggregation/shamir-s-secret-sharing] The strict condition that the size of the field must be larger than the number of shares must still be respected (e.g., if the number of shares could exceed 255, the field GF(256) might be replaced by say GF(65536)).
